Here is an example of how to avoid a circular refence, while still keeping 2 seperate interfaces.

```
// No @Mapper annotation, that is handled by the BasicAndNoteMapper.
public interface BasicMapper {
  // BasicMapper mapping method
}

// No @Mapper annotation, that is handled by the BasicAndNoteMapper.
public interface NoteMapper {
  // NoteMapper mapping method
}

@Mapper(componentModel = &quot;spring&quot;)
abstract class BasicAndNoteMapper implements BasicMapper, NoteMapper {
    // no methods needed, you can place the MapStruct annotations on the methods of the interface mappers.
}
```

This will result in 1 mapper implementation, but 2 separate interfaces. Important is that the interfaces do not have an `@Mapper` annotation, while the abstract class here does. The circular reference will now take place between methods instead of classes, which is not a problem.

